    {
      "@id": "ada:node/PALETTE.020",
      "@type": "ada:DesignCapsule",
      "label": "Two tiers: role tokens (chrome) vs pigment (meaning)",
      "summary": "tokens.ts splits the namespace: role tokens (bg/text/accent/focus…) skin the CHROME and can re-theme the whole shell from one file; the pigment palette in grammar.ts COLOUR_HEX carries MEANING (truth class, cluster identity, check class). Category and meaning never share a token.",
      "cluster": "PALETTE",
      "truth": "source",
      "checkClass": "C3",
      "depth": "L4",
      "from": "src/tui/ink/tokens.ts",
      "ada:whyItMatters": "Keeping the two channels separate is what stops a 10-colour graph reading as confetti and lets the shell be re-skinned without touching meaning-colour.",
      "ada:failureIfMissing": "Roles borrow from the area palette (today slate=body, rose=failure, cyan=link) so restyling the chrome silently changes what colours MEAN.",
      "parent": [
        "ada:node/ROOT.000"
      ],
      "child": [
        "ada:node/PALETTE.021",
        "ada:node/PALETTE.022",
        "ada:node/PALETTE.023",
        "ada:node/UNK.107"
      ],
      "dependsOn": [],
      "sibling": [
        "ada:node/PALETTE.021"
      ],
      "guardedBy": []
    },
    {
      "@id": "ada:node/PALETTE.021",
      "@type": "ada:DesignCapsule",
      "label": "60/30/10 earth discipline",
      "summary": "60% warm-dark base the eye rests on (bg/surface), 30% mid-earth structure & text, 10% accent that is the ONLY thing that pops or moves (accent/focus/selection). Every role is warm (terracotta family); cool pigments stay for meaning, never chrome.",
      "cluster": "PALETTE",
      "truth": "source",
      "checkClass": "C2",
      "depth": "L3",
      "from": "src/tui/ink/tokens.ts",
      "ada:whyItMatters": "A fixed ratio is what makes restraint reproducible instead of a vibe — it tells you when you've spent your accent budget.",
      "ada:failureIfMissing": "Accent leaks past 10% and the 'one warm pop' becomes wallpaper; nothing draws the eye because everything does.",
      "parent": [
        "ada:node/PALETTE.020"
      ],
      "child": [
        "ada:node/PALETTE.024"
      ],
      "dependsOn": [],
      "sibling": [
        "ada:node/PALETTE.024"
      ],
      "guardedBy": []
    },
    {
      "@id": "ada:node/PALETTE.022",
      "@type": "ada:DesignCapsule",
      "label": "Contrast is law — AA on every text role",
      "summary": "Every token used for TEXT must meet WCAG AA on bg #1B1410 (≥4.5:1 body, ≥3:1 large). This is pure math on the hex pair — checkable, no taste. The research already flags real failures (textMuted, slate-as-text, deep_blue).",
      "cluster": "PALETTE",
      "truth": "inference",
      "checkClass": "C5",
      "depth": "L3",
      "from": "docs/SURFACE-DESIGN.md",
      "ada:whyItMatters": "Legibility is the floor of 'premium'; a beautiful unreadable label is a defect, and contrast is the one design property that is fully deterministic.",
      "ada:failureIfMissing": "textMuted #7A6650 (~3.4:1) ships as body text on bg and low-vision users — who paid — cannot read the metadata.",
      "parent": [
        "ada:node/PALETTE.020"
      ],
      "child": [],
      "dependsOn": [],
      "sibling": [
        "ada:node/A11Y.081"
      ],
      "guardedBy": [
        "ada:check/contrast_aa"
      ]
    },
    {
      "@id": "ada:node/PALETTE.023",
      "@type": "ada:DesignCapsule",
      "label": "Capability-aware degradation ladder",
      "summary": "One codepath owns the fallback truecolor → 256 → 16 → mono. Detect level (supports-color/chalk.level), never hardcode the 16 ANSI indices for brand colours (the base16 remap trap) — use named RGB and let it downsample. tokens.ts already documents a 16-colour fallback per role.",
      "cluster": "PALETTE",
      "truth": "inference",
      "checkClass": "C4",
      "depth": "L3",
      "from": "src/core/grammar.ts",
      "ada:whyItMatters": "grammar.ts paint() emits raw 24-bit escapes unconditionally, which wash out over SSH/sudo/256-colour; the ladder makes earthy-and-legible survive every terminal.",
      "ada:failureIfMissing": "Brand colours render wrong or invisible on a 256-colour terminal; the user blames Ada for a 'broken' screen.",
      "parent": [
        "ada:node/PALETTE.020"
      ],
      "child": [],
      "dependsOn": [],
      "sibling": [
        "ada:node/A11Y.081"
      ],
      "guardedBy": [
        "ada:check/no_color_no_ansi"
      ]
    },
    {
      "@id": "ada:node/PALETTE.024",
      "@type": "ada:DesignCapsule",
      "label": "Category hues capped at ~7 — repeat, don't invent",
      "summary": "Cluster identity rotates through a fixed pigment set (plum, terracotta, cyan, sage, amber, green, slate, clay, deep_blue, rose); cap simultaneously-visible at ~7 and REPEAT a hue rather than invent a muddy in-between. Hue answers 'what area'; luminance (dim/normal/bold) answers 'how important'.",
      "cluster": "PALETTE",
      "truth": "inference",
      "checkClass": "C2",
      "depth": "L2",
      "from": "docs/SURFACE-DESIGN.md",
      "ada:whyItMatters": "Humans rank light/dark reliably but not colours; separating the two channels is what stops a many-cluster graph reading as confetti and degrades cleanly to mono.",
      "ada:failureIfMissing": "Each new area mints a new near-duplicate hue; at 10 clusters the tree is indistinguishable noise.",
      "parent": [
        "ada:node/PALETTE.021"
      ],
      "child": [],
      "dependsOn": [],
      "sibling": [
        "ada:node/LAYOUT.034"
      ],
      "guardedBy": []
    },
    {
      "@id": "ada:node/LAYOUT.030",
      "@type": "ada:DesignCapsule",
      "label": "Fixed skeleton: status / body / footer",
      "summary": "Status line top, body middle (flexGrow:1), hint/command bar pinned bottom — fixed forever. App.ts already nails this; protect it so the bottom bar truly pins and the body owns all slack.",
      "cluster": "LAYOUT",
      "truth": "source",
      "checkClass": "C3",
      "depth": "L3",
      "from": "docs/SURFACE-DESIGN.md",
      "ada:whyItMatters": "Spatial constancy is the cheapest trust signal in a TUI: the user always knows where identity, content, and actions live.",
      "ada:failureIfMissing": "Panes drift between screens; the footer floats mid-body; the user re-reads the layout every transition.",
      "parent": [
        "ada:node/ROOT.000"
